Great question! There are two ways to serve your `llms.txt` file. Since you're on **Vercel**, I'd recommend **Option B (Proxy Route)** — it keeps your file automatically updated whenever you re-run audits.

## Option A: Static File (Simplest)
Place the generated `llms.txt` file in your Vercel project's `public/` directory. It will be automatically served at `https://example.com/llms.txt`.

1. Download `llms.txt` from your Setup tab
2. Add it to your project's `/public` folder
3. Redeploy to Vercel
4. Verify at `https://example.com/llms.txt`

## Option B: Proxy Route (Recommended for Vercel) [1]
Set up a proxy that automatically fetches your file from FlowBlinq. This way, changes from future audits appear instantly without re-deploying.

1. In your `next.config.js` or via Vercel's rewrites, add:
   ```javascript
   async rewrites() {
     return {
       beforeFiles: [
         {
           source: '/llms.txt',
           destination: 'https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/{YOUR-SLUG}/llms.txt',
         },
         {
           source: '/llms-full.txt',
           destination: 'https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/{YOUR-SLUG}/llms-full.txt',
         },
         {
           source: '/.well-known/ucp.json',
           destination: 'https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/{YOUR-SLUG}/business.json',
         },
       ],
     };
   }
   ```

2. Replace `{YOUR-SLUG}` with your site's slug (visible in the proxy URLs shown in your Setup tab — typically derived from your domain, like `example-com`).

3. Deploy to Vercel.

**Which should you pick?**
- **Static (A)**: Faster, simpler, but requires redeploy on audit changes
- **Proxy (B)**: Always fresh, zero maintenance, slightly more setup

I'd go with **Proxy** for Vercel since deploys are quick and you get automatic updates. Ready to implement either?

# Nginx Configuration for FlowBlinq GEO

You're on the right page! The **Setup tab** should show you generated integration code with your domain slug already filled in. Look there first — it will have your specific URLs ready to paste.

## Basic Nginx Pattern

For Nginx, you'll add **location blocks** to proxy the GEO files from our service. Here's the pattern [1]:

```nginx
location = /llms.txt {
    proxy_pass https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/YOUR-SLUG/llms.txt;
}

location = /llms-full.txt {
    proxy_pass https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/YOUR-SLUG/llms-full.txt;
}

location = /.well-known/ucp.json {
    proxy_pass https://geo.flowblinq.com/api/serve/YOUR-SLUG/business.json;
}
```

**Replace `YOUR-SLUG`** with your domain slug (for `example.com`, that's `example-com`). The Setup tab will show your actual slug in the generated code.

## Where to Add It

Add these location blocks to your Nginx `server` block (usually in `/etc/nginx/sites-available/your-domain` or your vhost config), then reload:
```bash
sudo nginx -s reload
```

## Other Requirements

Beyond Nginx config, you'll also need to:
- **Tracking pixel**: Add an `<img>` tag to your site's HTML footer
- **robots.txt entries**: Add AI crawler rules (the Setup tab will show the exact lines)
- **Structured data** (optional but recommended): JSON-LD schema blocks

The Setup tab has all of these ready to copy. **Which files do you see in the Setup tab right now?** That will help me confirm what you need to deploy.

